@node what "What the h*** is this anyway??"

   FileListMaker is simply a door for AmiXpress which is able to make 
   a global filelist. It does this by merging the index-files for
   all the conferences the user has access to. So you can safely have a
   secret elitearea.

@endnode

@node instalation ""

   Pretty simple. First copy the doors-dir to your BBS-assign. Then do
   the same with then commands-dir. This should do it :)

   You might want to change the command name or the access-leve required
   for entering the door but i think you can do this yourself without a
   fancy installscript(If not - let me know :)

@endnode

@node configuration ""

   From v0.99e there will be a config.info in the Doors:Filelistmaker/ dir, 
   where you will be able to configure the door. At the moment the 
   following tooltypes is supported:

   HEADER=      The name and path of a textfile that should be in the start
                of the filelist.

   FOOTER=      Same as above - just in the bottom of the filelist.

   SCREEN=      Name and path of an ansi-screen to use instead of the 
                default FLM.Ansi.. *WARNING* I haven't had the time to test 
                this one, but it should work! :)

   FILELISTNAME=Name of the filelist. The door will automaticly put an
                .txt/.lha on the name.

@endnode

@node register ""

   In this beta-release I don't think it would be fair to let people 
   pay for the door. If you really hate the delay, then send a postcard, 
   email me, or call my BBS, and I will supply you with a "registrated"
   copy.

@endnode

@node todo ""

   I have still lots of ideas that should be implemented in the door 
   before it will be released to the public.

   1. You will be able to let the door make the filelist in RAM: which
      should make the creation of the filelist considerably faster.

   2. Make the seperator between each conf in the filelist configurable, 
      so you can make your own fance seperators :)

   3. Give you the posibility of using another packer than lha.

@endnode

